=041  \\$adut
=100  \\$aBuma, Johannes$d1694 -1756$4aut$96888
=245  \\$aBoere bruiloft, of Het huwelijk van Moddeworst, en Griet Beerdberg
=260  \\$aKnollendam$bs.n.$c1767
=336  \\$abook
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$aHighly amusing and very detailed poetical description of a country-wedding, written in rather an indecent language; A farcical play is inserted. Extensive commentaries and some other prose accompany the poem.
=500  \\$aJohannes Buma (Leeuwarden 1694 - Leeuwarden 1756), son of a pharmacist, practised that profession himself for some time, but after his father's death he turned to painting and poetry. De Boere Bruiloft (The Merry Wedding), a satire on various well-known Frisian persons, has a long history: according to the biography that precedes the work, Buma started writing it between the ages of thirty and forty, after which it remained unfinished for sixteen years. At the insistence of friends, he finally completed it. It was only eleven years after his death, when all those involved had died, that the poem was dared to be published to spare the feelings of the dramatis personae still in life.
=500  \\$aBeautiful mezzotint portrait of Buma by R. Jelgerhuis after R. Keyert.
=500  \\$anote in pencil "de koperen platen zijn nooit verschenen", refers to the Koperen Platen (engraved illustrations) mentioned on the title page, but do not appear in the book.

=041  \\$ager
=100  \\$aGerbert, Martin$d1720-1793$4aut$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q66625$96622
=245  \\$aReisen durch Alemannien, Welschland und Frankreich, welche in den Jahren 1759. 1760. 1761 und 1762. angestellet worden
=260  \\$aUlm, Frankfurt, Leipzig$bWohler$c1767
=300  \\$a[xvi]-478-[9]-[18] pages$billustrations, 9 unnumbered pages inserted, some folded
=336  \\$abook
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$aSoon after being appointed librarian of the monastery school in St. Blasien, Gerbert was sent on journeys from 1759 to 1762 for further education, which took him to Germany, Italy and France. He collected materials on the history of medieval liturgy and music and on the history of the monasteries and met many important personalities. Since Gerbert was initially entrusted with the administration of the monastery library, he began to study church history. The special object of his investigations became the history of church singing in the Middle Ages. Subsequently, he developed into an important music historian of modern times. His interest in music led to his acquaintance with Christoph Willibald Gluck, who became his friend. In 1760, during his travels, he collected copies of medieval treatises on music history and theory from monastery libraries. In Bologna he became friends with Padre Martini; both exchanged their rich experiences. The first result was the travel report 'Iter Alemannicum'.

=041  \\$aeng
=100  \\$aSmith, Robert$4aut$96924
=245  \\$aHarmonics$bor The Philosophy Of Musical Sounds
=250  \\$a1st ed.
=260  \\$aCambridge$bBentham$c1749
=300  \\$axvi-292-[13] pages$billustrations, 25 folded pages
=336  \\$abook
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$afacsimile edition see 05A22
=500  \\$aSmith (1689 - 1768) trained as a mathematician and was Plumian Professor of Astronomy at Cambridge for forty-four years (1716 - 1760). Although his work on harmonics has a mathematical basis, he approaches the problems of tuning keyboard instruments as a musician would. 
=500  \\$a"Music was both Smith's pastime and his other main scientific interest. He was an accomplished performer on several instruments, particularly the violoncello, and possessed a 'correct ear'. In his Harmonics he advocated the mean-tone temperament or method of tuning keyboard instruments. In the same work he contributed to the mathematical theory of music with an extended discussion of equal harmonic intervals." (Geoffrey Canton in the new Oxford DNB)

=041  \\$alat$agre
=100  \\$aEutropius$dafter 310-after 387$4aut$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q314694$96926
=245  \\$aBreviarium historiæ romanæ$bcum metaphrasi græca pæanii
=260  \\$aLeiden$bLuchtmans$c1793
=300  \\$aliv-[lxxviii]-772-[88] pages
=500  \\$aEutropius, a Roman historian, was active in the 4th century.His Summary of Roman History (Latin: Breviarium Historiae Romanae) is a ten-chapter compendium of Roman history from its foundation to the short reign of Jovian. The independent value of his Summary is small, but it sometimes fills a gap left by the more authoritative records. It is particularly useful to historians for its account of the First Punic War, as no copy of Livy's original books for that period have survived.
=500  \\$aContains also 'Metafrasi Graeca' by Pænius (Paian translation of the Roman history of Europe) e.a.
=500  \\$aAccording to Ton Koopman this copy could be a "prijsband van een stad" (prize book of a city). A prize book is a book that was given in the 16th-19th century to pupils who performed well at school. This phenomenon, which emerged in the 16th century, spread to Latin schools in the Netherlands in the 17th century. It disappeared in the Netherlands in the middle of the 19th century, but in other countries, such as England, prize books were still awarded deep into the 20th century to secondary school pupils who had achieved remarkably good grades. Such a book is called 'band' because it has a special bookmark of leather or parchment with a supralibros, a stamp in gold leaf of the town or school that financed the book, which makes it easily distinguishable from other books. This copy shows the Coat of Arms of the Dutch city Utrecht.

=245  \\$aLiber usualis missæ et officii pro domincis et festis cum cantu gregoriano
=260  \\$aParis; Tournai; Rome$bDesclée$c1939
=300  \\$axxix-[i]-1911-12-14-12-10 pages$bloose page (manuscript)
=336  \\$anotated music
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$aThe Liber Usualis is a book of commonly used Gregorian chants in the Catholic tradition (11th century), compiled by the monks of the Abbey of Solesmes in France. The Liber was first edited in 1896 by Solesmes Abbot Dom André Mocquereau (1849–1930). Its use has decreased since the Second Vatican Ecumenical Council (opened by Pope John XXIII in 1962), in the constitution on the liturgy (Sacrosanctum Concilium), allowed the local language to be used in Church rites.

=059  \\$aS A T B 2SA2T2B 2fl 2ob 3bsn 2tpt 2hrn timp 3vn 2vla vc org bc
=100  \\$aHandel, George Frideric$d1685-1759$4cmp$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q7302$94765
=240  \\$aAlexander's Feast, HWV 75
=245  \\$aAlexander's Feast, an Ode on Saint Cecilia's Day
=260  \\$aLondon$bArnold$cc. 1790
=300  \\$a141-[2] pages
=490  \\$aThe Works of G. F. Händel, Ed. in Score$vplate nos. 65-67
=500  \\$aHändel's Ode 'Alexander's Feast' (HWV 75) is set to a libretto by Newburgh Hamilton. Hamilton adapted his libretto from John Dryden's ode Alexander's Feast, or the Power of Music (1697) which had been written to celebrate Saint Cecilia's Day. Jeremiah Clarke (whose score is now lost) set the original ode to music.
=500  \\$aThe work describes a banquet held by Alexander the Great and his mistress Thaïs in the captured Persian city of Persepolis, during which the musician Timotheus sings and plays his lyre, arousing various moods in Alexander until he is finally incited to burn the city down in revenge for his dead Greek soldiers. 
=500  \\$aEnoch Hawkens (1793-1847) (07A20 Ex Libris ) was a famous singer (countertenor) in the 1830ies and 1840ies 
=501  \\$a07A20 is bound in with' An Ode or Serenata for the Birth Day of Queen Ann. Composed in the Year 1736'
=504  \\$aContains a List of Subscribers (after page 141).
=561  \\$a07A20 Ex Libris Enoch Hawkins (Plate)
=561  \\$a09L05 Ex Libris A. Bulckington 1798 and another name (ms on flyleaf and verso of tp) 
=590  \\$aThe Words by Dryden, Composed in the Year 1736 by G.F. Handel.

=041  \\$ager
=100  \\$aHarsdörffer, Georg Philipp$d1607-1658$4aut$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q66605$97319
=245  \\$aGesprachspiele, $bso bey Ehrn- und Tugendliebenden Gesellschaften aufzuüben$nvol. 3
=260  \\$aNuremberg$bEndter$c1643
=300  \\$a[xvii]-472-[48] pages$bmusic examples, illustrations$c9x14 cm, oblong
=500  \\$aContains plates (title-page, Erklärung, biv, 2, 20, 21, 156, 157, 159, 160, 162-164, 166, 167, 169-175, 185, 192, 200, 204, 212, 233, 241, 248, 251, 264, 266, 268, 346, 350, 353, and last page) and music
=500  \\$aSome notes in German handwriting in inner cover
=500  \\$aInfluenced by the French ideal of the "honnête homme", the "informed and socially polished type of man", in his "Frauenzimmer Gesprächspielen" the Nuremberg native takes his cue not least from the model and content of the public "Conférences" in Paris - the kind of informal gathering in which representatives of fiction and the education-hungry middle class, but no less so representatives of the natural sciences, debate "all the fine matters of physics, morals, mathematics and other disciplines". Because they combine "information and narration" in a variety of ways, combine "knowledge and intellectual pleasure", take the "delectare" of the ancient and humanistic dual purpose of literature alongside the "prodesse" really seriously, one rightly sees a "conversational aesthetic of 'impromptu'" at work in the layout of the "Gesprächspiele". These mind games of intellectual sociability were also part of the Italian Academies (such as the "Intronati", "Incogniti" and "Oziosi") Harsdörffer got in contact with during his Italian travels. Subjects of all kind are discussed in the form of a free conversation in which six persons, of both sexes and different ages, take part. 
=500  \\$aSubjects of all kind are discussed in the guise of a free conversation in which six persons, of both sexes and different ages, take part. A great number of fine copperplates, some emblematic, others taken from contemporary life, illustrate the text, so that the work has become a treasure house for literary research.
=500  \\$aConversation CXXX (p.170-242) seems to be a musical drama entitled 'Von der Welt Eitelkeit', offering information on libretto, cast, stagesets, music (instrumentation, score) & lighting. As the opera (allegorical shepherd's play) 'Seelewig' is found in the fourth volume on a libretto by Harsdörffer himself, and music composed by Sigmund Theophil Staden (1607-1655), this could probably be by the same team.
=500  \\$aFront plate (double paged) represents the company of six persons (a quartet and a duo) walking in a courtyard of a beautiful villa under a starry night sky, far from the world, as they turn to erudite, entertaining, perceptive conversation.
=534  \\$aThe 8 volumes of "(Frauenzimmer) Gesprachspiele" were published periodically (1643-1649), though not at regular intervals, and may thus be regarded as the forerunner of a literary magazine. Beginning with vol. 3 the word 'Frauenzimmer' is omitted, presumably in order not to frighten away male readers. 
=561  \\$aEx libris N. Ferber Hamburg 1876 (manuscript) and Dr. Med. Ferber 1882 (plate)
=590  \\$aSamt einer Zugabe genant: Melisa. Verfasset durch einen Mitgenossen der hochlöblichen Fruchtbringenden Geselschaft

=041  \\$adut
=245  \\$aVaderlandsche liederen voor het Genootschap van Wapenhandel,$b ter spreuk voerende: Voor Vrijheid en Vaderland $n1-6/6
=250  \\$a1st ed.
=260  \\$aLeiden$bHeyligert$c1784-86
=300  \\$a6 vols. (40+38+44+40+40+40 pages)$b1 folded page musical example
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$aCollection of Dutch patriotic songs
=500  \\$aThe "Schutterijen" in the cities of the Dutch Republic, were traditionally militias, citizen's rifle companies organised as guilds. 
Civilian armament was one of the tenets of the Patriot movement of the 1780s, which resulted in either the existing civic militias being put at the service of the Patriot movement or, in addition to the traditional militias, new companies were established under names such as 'exercitiegenootschappen' or 'genootschap tot de wapenhandel' (arms trade). (Arms trade here means the handling of weapons).

=500  \\$aThe Patriot movement set a lot of songwriters' pens in motion, among others:
Vaderlandsche liederen voor het Genootschap van Wapenhandel ter spreuke gevoerd 'Voor Vrijheid en Vaderland', of which the first volume appeared in 1784. Five sequels appeared in the following years. They included works by Pieter Vreede (1750-1837) and by Pieter van Schelle (1749-1792), F. van Aken, J. 't Hooft Jz. and others. 
=500  \\$aIn the Patriot songs, a number of themes recur regularly: freedom fighters from the classical and recent past, freedom and patriotism, the marching bands, events from the short history of the Patriot movement, the leaders of the Patriot movement, Christian themes of justice, and - in an antagonistic sense - the stadholder and his allies.
=501  \\$aBataviesche liederen

=041  \\$adut
=245  \\$aBataviesche liederen voor de vrye Nederlanders, $bonder de spreuk Uit Vryheid en Vaderlandsliefde
=260  \\$aAmsterdam$bWeege$c1785
=300  \\$a[91] pages
=336  \\$abook
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$a Collection of Dutch patriotic songs

=500  \\$aThe "Schutterijen" in the cities of the Dutch Republic, were traditionally militias, citizen's rifle companies organised as guilds.
Civilian armament was one of the tenets of the Patriot movement of the 1780s, which resulted in either the existing civic militias being put at the service of the Patriot movement or, in addition to the traditional militias, new companies were established under names such as 'exercitiegenootschappen' or 'genootschap tot de wapenhandel' (arms trade). (Arms trade here means the handling of weapons).

=500  \\$aThe Patriot movement set a lot of songwriters' pens in motion, among others:
'Vaderlandsche liederen voor het Genootschap van Wapenhandel' - of which the first volume appeared in 1784 & five sequels appeared in the following years - and 'Batavian songs for the free Dutch' published in Amsterdam for the society 'Tot Nut der Schutterij' (To the benefit of the militia) in 1785.
=500  \\$aIn the Patriot songs, a number of themes recur regularly: 
freedom fighters from the classical and recent past, freedom and patriotism, the marching bands, events from the short history of the Patriot movement, the leaders of the Patriot movement, Christian themes of justice, and - in an antagonistic sense - the stadholder and his allies. 
=501  \\$aVaderlandsche liederen voor het Genootschap van Wapenhandel

=500  \\$asee also H2-132
=500  \\$aIn 1682, a number of libretti appeared with a particular armillary printer's mark. Carl B. Schmidt attributes the printer's mark to an anonymous Amsterdam printer/publisher. He bases this attribution on the use of similar armillary printers' marks by Amsterdam printers, in particular the Elzeviers. Between 1682 and 1684 at least twelve little works appeared under this printer's mark, which together provide a good overview of Jean-Baptiste Lully's most important composed works up to that time.
=504  \\$aC.B. Schmidt, The livrets of Jean-Baptiste Lully's Tragédies Lyriques. A catalogue raisonné, New York 1995, 559.

=041  \\$afre$heng
=100  \\$aSwift, Jonathan$d1667-1745$4aut$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q41166$97332
=245  \\$aLe Conte du tonneau
=250  \\$aRev. ed.
=260  \\$aThe Hague$bScheurleer$c1741
=300  \\$a2 vols. ([xxiv]-300-[14]+[xiv]-286-[10] pages), 7 pages of plates$bTitle pages in red & black ink, engraved frontispiece, 7 inserted engraved plates
=520  \\$aA 'Tale of a Tub' (see also X1C18) was first published by the Irish clergyman and novelist Jonathan Swift in 1704; it is the first and perhaps most difficult of all his satires. The title is thought to refer to a dissenting priest’s pulpit, and the work is a biting parody on the religious extravagances that Swift perceived among the clergy at the start of the 18th century. The narrative is written using a complex though playful technique of interlinking stories concerning the lives of three brothers. particularly noteworthy for the woodcut illustrations that punctuate the text. For example, there is a striking image of a priest reprimanding the congregation down below, with a gallows and theatre shown in the background. The frontispiece also illustrates a whale distracted by a barrel thrown overboard by sailors: an allegory, perhaps, of how the text was designed to draw the attention of political and religious dissenters away from the affairs of the ‘ship’ of state.

=100  \\$aDesprez de Boissy, Charles$dc. 1730-1787$4aut$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q62934112$97333
=245  \\$aLettres sur les spectacles;$bavec une histoire des ouvrages pour et contre les théâtres
=246  \1$aLettres de M. Desp. de B., avocat au parlement, sur les spectacles
=250  \\$a4th ed.

=520  \\$aA work by the Jansenist lawyer Despez de Boissy against the theatre and shows, but above all against the attendance and the pleasures that will be sought there.
Rational and argued criticism of education and good morals and the pernicious roles of performances and in particular of theatre. The second volume is dedicated to the description of many volumes, including Italian ones, written over the years for or against theatrical performances.

=100  \\$aDubos, Jean-Baptiste$d1670-1742$4aut$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q432585$97334
=245  \\$aReflexions critiques sur la poésie et sur la peinture
=250  \\$a1st ed.
=260  \\$aParis$bMariette$c1719
=300  \\$a2 vols. ([viii]-692+[xii]-529-[2] pages)
=520  \\$aThe Réflexions critiques sur la poésie et sur la peinture is a work on the theory of art, the theory of literature and the theory of music by Jean-Baptiste Dubos, first published in 1719 and often republished since.
Taking Horace's hemistiche Ut pictura poesis as its epigraph, the Réflexions critiques sur la poésie et sur la peinture marked a turning point in aesthetic thought and was to exert a considerable influence on the development of theatrical art and music throughout the Enlightenment.

=100  \\$aGlazemaker, Jan Hendrik$d1620-1682$4trl$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q2221565$97337
=245  \\$aToonneel der wereltsche veranderingen.$bdoor deftige, vermakelijke en ware geschiedenissen afgebeelt,$n1-2/2
=250  \\$a1st ed.
=260  \\$aAmsterdam$bHilten, van; Doornick$c1648; 1659
=300  \\$a2 vols. ([viii]-554 + [viii]-562 pages)$bbound in white vellum, illustrations, engraved title page
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$avol. 1 is published by van Hilten, vol. 2 by Doornik
=500  \\$aGlazemaker was a Dutch translator of almost 70 books, mostly from Latin and from French. Glazemaker probably lived and worked in Amsterdam, where most of his translations were published. He may have been the first person in history to make a living primarily by translating into Dutch. While much of his output was of the Latin classics, he was particularly noted for his translations of the writings of René Descartes from both French and Latin.
=500  \\$aA considerable number of the stories are translations of writings by the highly productive Bishop of Belley, Jean Pierre Camus, who in that first half of the century published some 960 short stories - in 21 collections - in addition to another 15 more or less substantial novels. Bishop at the age of 25, Camus felt called upon to counterbalance all the frivolities and absurdities he felt were appearing in this field with his stories and novels. The stories he published pretended to be true, since they were presented as examples of how things can go wrong when a person does not comply with Christian standards of a good life. To this end, they were usually provided with edifying introductions and conclusions. Glazemaker omitted these in his translations, which, had he known it, would undoubtedly have saddened Camus greatly. This left relatively short accounts of murders, rapes, adulteries and so on, which the reader was supposed to assume really happened, just as the reader of a newspaper is supposed to believe in the reality of mixed messages. But in between, Glazemaker included stories in his collection that apparently did not care about whether they really happened but about how striking the story is. 
=590  \\$adaar in, onder hoge en lage staten van menschen, zuivere liefden, schrikkelijke veinzingen, spitze vonden, bevallijke antwoorden, wrede moorden, verwoede wraken, rechtvaardige straffen en ontellijke sporeloze hertstochten spelen. Uit verscheide schrijvers

=041  \\$ager$aeng
=100  \\$aHirsch, Paul$d1881-1951$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q2060211$4col$4edt$97450
=245  \\$aKatalog der Musikbibliothek Paul Hirsch, Frankfurt am Main$nvols. 3-4
=260  \\$aFrankfurt am Main$aCambridge$bHirsch$bCambridge University Press$c1936$c1947
=300  \\$a2 vols. ([vii-362 + xxiii-695 pages)$bplates, illustrations, facsililes, music examples, photographs
=500  \\$aPaul Adolf Hirsch was a German industrialist. He was also a musician, bibliophile and musicologist who assembled the largest private music library in Europe. The Hirsch Collection is now housed at the British Library.
=500  \\$aHirsch, an accomplished violinist, took a keen interest in publications concerning all aspects of music—performance, history and theory. In 1896 he began to collect historical musical works, focusing on early printed editions of Haydn, Mozart and Beethoven, 19th-century opera and early theoretical works. In 1922 Hirsch hired musicologist Kathi Meyer (later Meyer-Baer) as a research assistant and opened the library to the public two days a week. Hirsch and Meyer began compiling a catalog of the library contents. 
=500  \\$aThe first three volumes were originally published by Martin Breslauer, Berlin, and were reprinted by Morsum/Sylt:Cicero Presse of Hamburg in 1993. The fourth volume, which includes addenda to the first three, was completed in Cambridge with the help of Edith Schnapper and Hirsch's daughters, Irene Hartogs-Hirsch and Renate Schuster.
Vol. 1: Theoretische Drucke bis 1800. (1928)
Vol. 2: Opern-Partituren. (1930)
Vol. 3: Instrumental- und Vokalmusik bis etwa 1830. (1936)
Vol. 4: Erstausgaben, Chorwerke in Partitur, Gesamtausgaben, Nachschlagewerke etc. Ergänzungen zu Bd. 1–3. Cambridge University Press (1947)
=500  \\$aVol. 3, subtitled "Instrumental- und Vokalmusik bis etwa 1830", was published in 1936 in Frankfurt a.M., in the series 'Veröffentlichungen der Musikbibliothek Paul Hirsch', 2. series, vol. 3
=500  \\$avol. 4, subtitled "Erstausgaben, Chorwerke in Partitur, Gesamtausgaben, Nachschlagwerke etc. Ergänzungen zu Bd. I-III" was published in 1947 in Cambridge
=500  \\$aVol. 4 contains an autograph dedication to Alex Hyatt King:" "... That place, that does contain my books, the best companions, is to me a glorious court, where hourly I converse with the old sages and philosophers..." (John Fletcher). If my friend Alex. H. King replaces the word "old" by "young", this should be a very apt inscription for this copy of my Volume IV. London, at the B.M., January 6th, 1948, Paul Hirsch"
=504  \\$aVol.4 contains indexes
=561  \\$aVol. 4 contains an autograph dedication to Alex Hyatt King
=563  \\$aBound in white vellum, with cardboard front and back cover

=500  \\$aAndries Pels was the co-founder, with Lodewijk Meyer, of the society Nil Volentibus Arduum (1669), which is mentioned in manuscript on the spine
=500  \\$aluxurious print with a beautiful, pastoral title-page, see preface: "Wy hebben u van tydt tót tydt médegedeeld alle de stukken door het Kunstgenootschap Nil Volentibus Arduum uitgegeeven, en geene moeite, vlyt, nóch kósten gespaard, om die Dichtwérken glans en luister by te zétten, zo door het versiere van ieder stuk met een zinlyke Tytelprent, ontworpen en gesneeden door kunstryke Meesters, als ook om het wérk zelve te doen verschynen, op zeer fraai papier met nétte druklétteren, indiervoegen dat niemand met récht ons iets béters zou kunnen afvórderen. Hier toe zyn wy niet alleen genoopt door liefde tót de kunst, maar ook door weêrzien in het zien der valsche naadrukken, t'elkens door baatzuchtige Ménschen den luiden in de handen gestooken, om ons goed oogmérk te dwarsboomen"

=041  \\$ager
=100  \\$aSlevogt, Gottlieb$dabout 1694-1732$4aut$97457
=245  \\$aGründliche Untersuchung von denen Rechten der Altäre, Tauf-Steine, Beicht-Stühle, Predigt-Stühle, Kirch-Stunde, Gottes-Künsten, Orgeln, Kirchen-Musik, Glocken, Thürmer und Gottes-Aecker$baus dem Canonischen und Protestantischen Kirchen-Recht erläutert
=260  \\$aJena$bRitter$c1732
=300  \\$a[xxxii]-517-[7] pages$bfrontispiece black & red, illustration, leather cover
=336  \\$abook
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$aSlevogt was born at the end of the 17th century (details conspicuously unknown) in Jena, where he studied, received his doctorate in 1716 and devoted himself to the practice of law. He died in February 1732 as a ducal Altenburg court and government advocate and imperial comes palatinus, but left behind a heavy burden of debt, so that his family declined completely. Slevogt's writings belong mainly to Protestant canon law, which they treat sometimes historically-archaeologically, sometimes practically. His German work on the law of the altars combines both points of view with a mildly reasonable appreciation and toleration of all ceremonial activity.
=504  \\$aindex
=590  \\$anebst einer Einleitung von der innerlichen und äusserlichen Gestalt der ersten Kirchen. Mit einer Vorrede Herrn Just Henning Böhmers, weitberühmten ICti, königl. Preußischen Hochbetrauten Geheimbden Raths und Directoris der Königl. Friedrichs-Universität zu Halle, wie auch Prof. Publ. Ordinarii, von dem Schaden der Menschen-Satzungen bey dem Kirchen-Wesen

=100  \\$aLa Feillée, François de$dc. 1700-1763$4aut$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q105946728$95432
=245  \\$aMéthode pour apprendre parfaitement les règles du plain-chant et de la psalmodie;$bAvec des Messes et autres Ouvrages en Plain-chant figuré et musical, à voix seule et en partie, à l'usage des Paroisses.
=260  \\$aAvignon$bGarrigan$c1815
=300  \\$aiv-492 pages
=336  \\$abook
=336  \\$aprinted
=336  \\$anotated music
=500  \\$aLa Feillée, French botanist & abbot, was attached to the choir of Chartres Cathedral, in the mid 18th Century. By 1745, he was a composer and "theorist" at the Poitiers Cathedral. We owe him an abridged antiphonary, published in Paris by Hérissant in 1751, this manual of plainchant and some compositions.

=041  \\$aeng
=100  \\$aSimpson, Christopher$d1605-1669$4aut$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q731249$97500
=245  \\$aA Compendium of Practical Musick in Five Parts
=250  \\$a1st ed.
=260  \\$aLondon$bGodbid$c1667
=300  \\$a[xvi]-176-[2]-6 pages$bengraved frontispiece, music examples
=500  \\$aAccording to Rebecca Herrisone (Manchester U, message to Eline Holl, 21 March 2020): "it is a special copy, which probably indicates some kind of interim stage between the 2nd and 3rd editions of the Compendium. That is, the passage printed in your Appendix is included in the 1678 edition (p. 94, downloadable from EEBO) — placed exactly as Simpson requests in the pre-amble to the Appendix – but not in the 1667 edition proper, so the version you have seems to have the later addition of this material pre-empted. The content of the Appendix is therefore material that is already known from the 1678 edition. However, I wasn’t aware that Simpson had written it earlier to include with copies of the 1667 edition. From the reproduction I assume that the Appendix forms a separate gathering, starting with the Errata list on the recto; we can’t really tell, then, at what point the addition was made: clearly proof-reading had identified the errors listed in the Errata, but this could have been done at any point after printing itself, so could come any time between 1667 and the later addition. However, Simpson’s text at the start of the Appendix clearly indicates that he doesn’t yet know if there will be another edition, and there is therefore some implication that the Appendix is relatively close in date to the 1667 edition itself."

=500  \\$aCompilation of information taken from books by Vander Straeten (1885-1894), Grégoir (1865) and Fétis (1864)
=500  \\$aMors, also Moors, de Moor, was a family of southern Dutch organists and organ builders with the emphasis on the latter. During the 16th century the Mors family spread the organ art of the Southern Netherlands in Northern Germany, just as the Brebos family did in Spain and Langhedul in France.

=100  \\$aMontazet, Antoine de $d1713-1788$4edt$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q2856902$921934
=245  \\$aRituel du Diocèse de Lyon
=260  \\$aLyon$bde la Roche$c1787
=300  \\$a2 vols. in 1 (xxxvi-436+404 pages)$bmusical notation, 2 engraved frontispieces
=500  \\$aIn part 2 (p. 225 etc): musical notation and information on plainchant.
=520  \\$aAntoine de Montazet (17 August 1713-2 May 1788) was a French theologian, of Jansenist tendencies, who became bishop of Autun and archbishop of Lyon. He was elected to the Académie française in 1756. Contrary to the papal bull of Pope Pius V on the Roman Breviary, Montazet changed the text of the Breviary and the Missal. The later efforts of Pope Pius IX and Cardinal Bonald to suppress the innovations of Montazet provoked resistance on the part of the canons, who defended the traditional Lyonnese ceremonies (Wikipedia).

=500  \\$aFacsimile of an edition from 1525
=500  \\$aIn the back, note in pensil "Strassburger Ex. im Jahre 1870 wohl verbrannt, daher ist diese Nachbildung dest(o) gesucht" ("Strasbourg copy probably burnt in 1870, therefore this replica is the more sought after")
=500  \\$aProtestantism in Strasbourg is an important aspect of the history and sociology of the city. The Protestant Reformation was introduced in Strasbourg as early as 1518, when Matthieu Zell preached in Strasbourg in the Lutheran manner. In 1520, Pierre-Philippe de Remiremont preached the Reformation in the church of Saint-Pierre-le-Vieux in Strasbourg. In 1524, the pastor Martin Bucer moved to the church of Sainte-Aurélie in Strasbourg, outside the walls of Old Strasbourg, and then 1531 to the church of Saint Thomas in Strasbourg. In 1529 the cathedral was given over to Protestant worship. The city officially joined Lutheranism in 1532.

=500  \\$aJohann Lauremberg, also Johannes Lauremberg, occasionally incorrect: Johann Wilhelm Laurenberg (* 26 February 1590 in Rostock; † 28 February 1658 in Sorø, Denmark) was a mathematician and cartographer as well as a Low German poet and writer of the Baroque period. As a pseudonym he used the name "Hans Willmsen L. Rost." (= Johann, son of Wilhelm Lauremberg Rostochiensis).
=500  \\$afascinating volume in Low German or Low Saxon (Niedersächsisch / Nederduits)
=500  \\$aThe satirical Veer Schertzgedichte, in which Lauremberg mocks fashionable follies of his time, were translated into High German by Constantin Christian Dedekind in 1654,  and was newly published under the title "De nye poleerte Utiopische Bockes-Büdel. o. J." (c. 1700)

=245  \\$aAve Maria ponderada$bnovena da Immaculada Conceiçaõ da sempre Virgem Maria Mãy, e protectora dos Frades Menores

=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$aA novena (from Latin: novem, "nine") is an ancient tradition of devotional praying in Christianity, consisting of private or public prayers repeated for nine successive days or weeks. The prayers are often derived from devotional prayer books, or consist of the recitation of the rosary (a "rosary novena"), or of short prayers through the day. Novena prayers are customarily printed in small booklets, and the novena is often dedicated to a specific angel, saint, Marian title of the Blessed Virgin Mary, or one of the persons of the Holy Trinity.
=500  \\$aAs the author Fr. Bernardo de Santa Maria Rosa was preacher and Master of Ceremonies of the Royal Convent of S. Francisco da Cidade do Porto, it could well be that this prayer/songbook was used at the Novenas for the Virgin in the liturgic rituals at the abbey mentioned. The feast day of the Virgin of the Immaculate Conception is 8 December.
=500  \\$aEngraved Frontispiece, iconography of the Virgin of the Immaculate Conception shows her standing, with arms outstretched or hands clasped in prayer.

=100  \\$aManassès de Pas de Feuquières, Antoine de$cMarquis$d1648 - 1711$4aut$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q587269$97698
=245  \\$aLettres et négociations du Marquis de Feuquières$bAmbassadeur extraordinaire du Roi en Allemagne, en 1633 & 1634$nvols. 1-2/3
=250  \\$a1st ed.

=300  \\$a2 vols. ([vi]-ccxx-291+478 pages)
=336  \\$abook
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$aVol. 3 is lacking
=500  \\$aAntoine de Pas, Marquis de Feuquières (1648 - 1711) was a French writer and soldier, who served in the wars of Louis XIV. His "Mémoires de M. le Marquis de Feuquiere, lieutenant general des armées du roi: contenans les maximes sur la guerre, & l'application des exemples aux maximes" ran to 42 editions between 1736 and 2014 and was translated into three languages. Completed just before his death in 1711, it was highly critical of Louis XIV and remained unpublished until 1736. Voltaire later used it as a source for his own work, "Siècle de Louis XIV". 
=500  \\$a The book begins with a long biographical presentation of the marquis written by the abbot Gabriel Pérau to whom  we owe this edition. 
=500  \\$aParticularly comprehensive, it includes a good understanding of the importance that France had in the Thirty Years' War and the particularly fundamental role of the Marquis de Feuquières in the formation of the alliance against the House of Austria.
=504  \\$ahttps://www.librairie-siblot.fr/images/2012/03/Lettres-et-n%c3%a9gociations-du-Marquis-de-Feuqui%c3%a8res-17532.pdf
=561  \\$aex libris Albert Verwey, (Plate) containing the motto "In de boeken mag men 't zoeken, in der minnen zal men 't vinnen"

=500  \\$aThe evangelical pastor Johann Spangenberg studied in Erfurt and later officiated in Hardegsen in the line of Martin Luther, while developing his talent as an organist and composer. He wrote his study on music in 1533 and his important collection of liturgical chant in 1545.

=008  210720s1653\\\\||||||||\||||\00|\0\fre\d
=041  \\$afre
=100  \\$aJoly, Claude$d1607-1700$4aut$97709
=245  \\$aRecueil de maximes véritables et importantes pour l'institution du Roy
=260  \\$aParis$bElsevier$c1653
=300  \\$a[xxii]-584-[2] pages$bgilded pages
=336  \\$abook
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$aThe most prominent rebellions in the mid-seventeenth century France were those of the nobles and the judges and known as the 'Fronde'.The leading theoretician of the parleamentary fronde was Claude Joly. His treatise 'Recueil de maximes' is a collection of constitutionalist maxims, remnants of a pre-absolutist age, and include trenchant attacks on two contributions of Cardinals Richelieu and Mazarin to political thought and practice in France. One was the new motion that the king is rightly the master - in effect the owner - of the persons and properties of all inhabitants of France. The other was the Machiavellian view that succesful public policy requires the systematic use of immoral means. The King's power, warned Joly, is limited and not automatically sanctionned by divine law. Frenchmen posess just title to their lives and properties, and are not the slaves of a despot or tyrant. The king's original divine power is mediated through the French people, Joly added, and the king cannot rightfully tax the French without the consent of the states-general. The fact that Joly was reviled by the king and his party as a rebel and a traitor, he declared, shows that the old constitutionhas been overcome by new views holding the king to have unlimited authority above all law. For Joly this view was 'pure usurpation'  bred in the 'monstrous cauldron' of Machiavel.

=245  \\$aLe Rollin de la jeunesse ou Morceaux choisis des histoires ancienne et romaine$bTome second. Histoire Romaine$nVol.2
=250  \\$a2nd ed.
=260  \\$aParis$bDelaunay$c1816
=300  \\$a492 pages$billustrations
=336  \\$abook
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$aCharles Rollin (1661-1741) was a French historian and educator, very popular in his time. His literary work dates chiefly from the later years of his life, when he had been forbidden to teach. His once famous Ancient History (French: Histoire Ancienne, 12 vols., Paris, 1730–38) and the less generally read Roman History (Histoire Romaine, only five of nine volumes finished by the time of his death) were avowed compilations, uncritical and somewhat inaccurate. But they instructed and interested, generation after generation.

=100  \\$aVerdussen, Cornelius$4aut$97729
=245  \\$aCatalogus quorumdam librorum prostantium in officina viduæ Cornelii Verdussen & consortis Bibliopolæ Antverpiæ
=260  \\$aAntwerp$bs.n.$c17xx
=300  \\$a4 pages
=336  \\$abook
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$aVerdussen was a dynasty of printers in Antwerp, starting with Hieronymus Verdussen I in the late sixteenth century, and ending around 1800. Many other printers in Antwerp were also related to the Verdussens through marriage. They specialized in religious works and works in Spanish,[1] but also published newspapers, almanachs, poetry, scientific works, .... By the end of the 17th century, they produced about 21% of the Spanish books printed in the Netherlands, and with 5 presses was second only to Moretus in Antwerp.

=500  \\$aVossius was a Dutch Protestant theologian, linguist, historian and humanist (1577-1649). He was amongst the first scholars to treat both Christian theological dogma and non-Christian religion from a scientific-historical, instead of a theological point of view. He was regarded as a homo universalis because he involved himself in many fields of science.

=100  \\$aBredero, Gerbrand Adriaenszoon$d1585-1618$4aut$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q560740$94858

=336  \\$abook
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$aOriginally published in 1616
=500  \\$aLucelle is a true Romeo & Juliet adaptation by Bredero. A play that moved Maria Tesselschade to tears at the premiere in 1615, a play that was immortalised many times by painters such as Jan Steen and Jan Miense Moleaer, a play that was reprinted more than any of Bredero's plays in the 17th and 18th centuries, a play with the recognisable topical emotion of unattainable love due to a difference in descent.
=500  \\$aFinal scene of the play painted by Molenaer:
https://www.pubhist.com/w7503

=500  \\$aBredero signs the play with 'overgeset en gerijmt' (translated and put in rhymes), pointing herewith at the fact that this tragicomedy was based on a foreing template, namely the ‘tragi-comedie en prose ’ Lucelle (1576) by the French writer Louis Le Jars

=041  \\$adut
=245  \\$aEpitaphium, ofte graf-dicht op 't overlyden vanden sinrijcken Poeets G. A. Brederode
=260  \\$as.l.$bs.n.$cs.d.
=300  \\$a[14] pages
=500  \\$aElegies after the death of Bredero. 
=500  \\$aDigitized later edition at https://www.dbnl.org/tekst/stui002memo01_01/stui002memo01_01_0041.php
=500  \\$aOriginal title page (with portrait of Bredero) is missing (cut out?)
=500  \\$aThis edition of Elegies (Lijck-dichten) shows clearly the status of Bredero as a local celebrity at that very moment. Such a publication was unprecedented, and it demonstrates how popular the poet was among his fellow citizens. They all strongly and intensely experienced the loss. The elegies were written by different poets, including famous Dutch authors like Samuel Coster, Petrus Scriverius and Joost van den Vondel. It marks Bredero’s decease as a moment at which Amsterdam authors sing the praises of their popular and much-loved former colleague. The poems predominantly breathe the usual funeral topics of praise, grief and consolation. But the very first of all these poems, a lengthy `Epitaph, or elegy on the death of the significant poet G.A. Bredero’ (`Epitaphium. Oft Graf-dicht Op ’t overlyden vanden sinrijcken Poeet G.A. Brederood’), tells its readers how Bredero died a sudden death, (probably heart failure).

=590  \\$aWelches die Melodien derer so wohl alten als neuen biß hieher eingeführten Gesänge unsers Teutschlandes in sich hält auch durch eine besondere Einrichtung dergestalt verfasset ist, daß diejenige Lieder, so man nicht zu singen gewußt, nunmehro mit ihren behörigen Melodien gesungen, und mit der Orgel oder Clavier accompagnirt werden können. =336  \\$atext
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$aCited in Koopman 1985, 107
=500  \\$aTheoretical dictionary of the three fine arts of painting, sculpture and architecture as well as of poetry and music.
=500  \\$aTitle-page engraving by Daniel Chodowiecki  (1726-1801), German-Polish painter and printmaker. Allegory of the fine arts: the picture shows a light female figure surrounded by Minerva and the Graces. Minerva sits with lance and medusa shield. At her feet are tools for carving stone, a palette, brush, compass and square, masks and cothurn, a shawm and a plectrum. Minerva looks up at the female figure standing next to her, her gaze directed into the distance as if listening to an inner voice. A bright sun shines above the standing one. Minerva points with her hand to the instruments on the floor which refer to the three fine arts of painting, sculpture and architecture as well as to poetry and music.the three graces, meanwhile, are busy endowing the standing female figure with attributes that point to various arts. In the background, a landscape opens up in the depths, in which a naked, still uncivilised human family sits in front of a kind of primitive hut while one of them chases a deer. (Veronika Mertens, Die drei Grazien, Studien zu einem Bildmotiv in der Kunst der Neuzeit, Harrassowitz Verlag, 1994)
=534  \\$aOriginally published in 1771-74

=300  \\$a4 volumes ([xiv]-136+[vi]-246-[2]+[vi]-188-[2]+[iv]-277-[3] pages)
=500  \\$aManifesto of radical Enlightenment.
=500  \\$aBalthasar Bekker (20 March 1634 – 11 June 1698) was a Dutch minister and author of philosophical and theological works. Opposing superstition, he was a key figure in the end of the witchcraft persecutions in early modern Europe.
=500  \\$a4 volumes in 2, with the author's signature on all four volumes below 'Beright'

Noodig verweer-schrift voor den Nederduitschen Kerken-raadt van Utrecht
Wederlegging van het zoogenaamde verweerschrift voor de Nederduitze Kerkenraad van Utrecht en het kortbondig vertoog van de onbetamelykheid en schadelykheid der comedien
Bekentmaking van het roekeloos bestaan van Pieter Burman, vermaart Professor in de Akademie van Utrecht

=590  \\$aOder gantz natürliche Abbildung solcher Gelehrten, die da vermeynen alle Gelehrsamkeit und Wissenschafften verschlucket zu haben, auch in dem Wahn stehen, daß ihres gleichen nicht auf Erden zu finden, wannenhero sie alle andere Menschen gegen sich verachten, einen unerträglichen Stoltz und Hochmuth von sich spüren lassen; in der That aber doch selber so, wie sie in ihrer Haut stecken, Ignoranten, Pedanten, ja Ertz-Fantasten und tumme Sympel sind, die von der wahren Gelehrsamkeit, womit die Weisheit verknüpffet seyn muß, weit entfernet. Nebst einer lustigen Dedication und sonderbaren Vorrede. Dergleichen verkehrten Gelehrten zur guten Lehre, und verhoffentlich daraus fliessenden Besserung; andern aber, so sich denen Studiis widmen, und noch Anfänger sind, zur getreuen Warnung, auch sonst jederman zum Vergnügen geschrieben

=590  \\$ain Nederduytse sang-versen, oude en nieuwe rymen : begrypende d'oude, alle de van ouds in gebruyk zynde Psalmen, eertyds gerymt door Willem van Haagt: en de nieuwe, alle de buyten gebruyk geblevene Psalmen, namaals van hare onbekende, op bekende kerk-sangwysen gestelt en gerymt, door J. v. Aldus geheel op bekende Sang-wysen, benevens alle de gewone geestelyke liederen, tendienste van de christelyke gemeynten van d'onveranderde Augsburgsche Geloofs-Belydenis, in 't ligt gegeven en met eenige nieuw-geapprobeerde liederen vermeerdert. In desen druk de sang-noten en eenige oude rymen, &c. van vele fauten gesuyvert

=041  \\$alat
=100  \\$aZehentner, Paul$d1589-1648$4aut$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q55874362$97979
=245  \\$aPromontorium malæ spei: impiis periculose navigantibus propositum
=250  \\$a1st ed.
=260  \\$aHaupt; Widmanstadt$bGraz$c1643
=300  \\$a[xxxviii]-752-[10] pages$bgilt edges, 2 engravings
=336  \\$abook
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$aJesuit warning of the consequences of licentiousness ("Promontory, thoughts of hope for the wicked goal that sailed dangerously. Whether it is a sign of rejection and note: procrastination of repentance written precautionary men's amendment is reluctance, sometimes hope to repent.")
=500  \\$aFirst and only edition of a Latin edifying text on moral and religious issues by the Jesuit Paul Zehentner (1589-1648), preacher at the Graz court of the widow of the Holy Roman Emperor Ferdinand II and teacher of grammar, the humanities and the Holy Scripture at Millestadt in Austria. A moral-theological treatment of state theory, astrology and magic, intended to highlight the dangers of licentious behaviour. 
=500  \\$aIt provides our first known reference to the tragedy of Leontius, a play Zehentner saw at the Jesuit University in Ingolstadt in 1615, and which was to serve as a prototype for the Don Juan legend (Keefe, Mozart studies, p. 140). 
=500  \\$aZehentner dedicated the book to Leonardus Helfridus, Count at Maggau, 26 October 1643, and received a privilege from the Holy Roman Emperor Ferdinand III.
=500  \\$aEngraved allegorical frontispiece and a richly designed armorial and emblematic dedication plate, both by David Tscherning.
=504  \\$aindex
=590  \\$aSive, signum & nota reprobationis: procrastinatio poenitentiae, scripta cautelae hominum, emendatione[m] vita[e] cunctantium, spe aliquando resipiscendi.
=610  \0$aJesuits$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q36380$921140

=245  \\$aSystem der Musik-Wissenschaft und der praktischen Composition
=260  \\$aBerlin$bLogier$c1827
=300  \\$axii-346-[4]-13 pages$bmusical examples, frontispiece illustration
=336  \\$abook
=336  \\$amusical notation
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$aIn 1822 Logier was called to Berlin to help found a music academy, and subsequently trained elementary teachers on behalf of the king until 1826. In addition, the publishing house of his brother Wilhelm published his textbooks in German.  In this method, several pupils are taught at a time, with technical instruction done together with instruction in principles of harmony. This lay the basis of group teaching in music.

=336  \\$anotated music
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$aA blind 18th century musician based in London, Starling Goodwin wrote music both for church use and public concerts. Surviving examples of his work include voluntaries for organ or harpsichord and a number of popular light entertainment songs. One of the greatest pluralists of his profession, he was organist at four London churches simultaneously at the time of his death. He was also a witty and amusing socialiser and an accomplished violinist.

=008  210628s1745\\\\\\\||k||\||||\00|\0\mul\d
=041  \\$adut$alat
=041  \\$alat
=059  \\$av
=245  \\$aMissen en gezangen
=250  \\$a1st ed.
=260  \\$aUtrecht$bWeyde, van der$c1745
=300  \\$a[i]-48-[2] pages
=336  \\$anotated music
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$aThe so-called 'Stukjesboek', which formed the basis of the old Catholic church song in the Netherlands: 98 songs in Latin and Dutch, plus three ordinaria in Latin. Strong Jansenist influence.
=500  \\$aMissen en Gezangen is not the only para-liturgical hymnbook that the Utrecht Church had after the schism of 1723.
Some of the material it contains had already been published in Het Paradijs, which appeared in eight editions between 1621 and 1679 in Antwerp, or in Het Prieel, Brugues 1609/l0. Also the collection of Gulielmus de Swaen, parish priest in Gouda, to which he gave the name Den Singende Swaen'[, -an allusion to his own name, which means 'swan', - contains pieces that can be found in Missen en Gezangen. Of a substantial part, however, the origin remains obscure. No doubt a large repertoire of Latin and Dutch hymns was known from the rather isolated milieu of the Utrecht church. It is even possible that the type of hymns found in Missen en Gezangen and the other collections mentioned, were cherished by the secular clergy and that their use was discouraged, more or less, by the regulars. It is at least curious that in the Old Catholic Church an abundance of hymns have survived, while they are relatively rare in the Roman Catholic Church parishes in Friesland and northern Holland.
=500  \\$aIn Missen en Gezangen we find texts by Andreas van der Schuur and Jean Baptiste Stalpaert van der Wielen , but most of the texts are from the Counter-Reformation period and are anonymous.
=500  \\$aAndreas van der Schuur (also Van der Schuer) (1656- 1719) was ordained a priest in 1680 and became parish priest in Vianen in 1692. Archbishop Van Neercassel entrusted him with the translation of the Bible  in 1732, completed by H. van Rhijn. He was the composer of several religious poems, both Latin and Dutch.


=500  \\$aJean Baptiste Stalpa(e)rt van der Wiele(n) (1579 - 1630), a lawyer in The Hague in 1598,  became a priest in 1606. In 1613 he was appointed parish priest in Delft, where he remained until his death. In 1621 he published "Hemelrijk", in 1622 "Het vrouwelick cieraed van St Agnes", religious poetry. In prose he published "Roomsche Reys" in 1624, and in 1628 a collection of hymns "'t
Gulden Jaer ons'Heeren Jesu Christi". As a posthumous work he published "Extractum Catholicum" and "Guide Jaers Feestdaghen of de Schat der gheestelijekeLofsanghen", in 1631 and 1634. He was the composer of about 2000 hymns.

=260  \\$aPérigueux; Couze; Bordeaux; Bergerac$c1795-1829

=500  \\$aCorrespondence addressed to Schröder and Schylen, traders in the Chatrons in Bordeaux (and some others),  dated between the year Germinal 3 (march 1795) and 1829. 53 letters signed for the most part by Desmartis and Choiet, traders in Bergerac (2 from Courtois in Perigueux and 1 from Dumare in Couze) The Correspondence concerns the delivery of wine. 51 postmarks from Bergerac and 2 from Perigueux. (info Antiquarian)
=500  \\$aThe Bergerac & Périgord (Courtois & Couze) were wine-growing regions, a subregion of South West France,  which corresponds roughly to the current  Dordogne Department. Bordeaux, hub of the famed wine-growing region, is a port city on the Garonne River in southwestern France.

=500  \\$aengraved frontispiece "Fame honours the Guida Armonica"  by Simon François Ravenel l'Ancien (1706-1774) after Edme Bouchardon (1698-1762). Fame hovers in the air above the sea (where a boat is floating) and a beach where there is a globe, symbols of the arts (flute and score, bust, palette and brushes, compass) and a military trophy (armour, helmet, shield, sword, arrows), probably alluding to the Prince of Wales, the musician's patron.

=500  \\$aYearbook of the Katharineum in Lübeck, a gymnasium famous for its curriculum of the trivium (grammar, rhetoric and logic), the quadrivium (arithmetic, geometry, music, and astronomy), as well as the study of literature, poetry, drama, philosophy, history, art, and languages.

=100  \\$aMartini, Jean-Paul-Égide$d1741-1816$4cmp$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q696034$96173
=245  \\$aAirs du Droit du Seigneur et trois romances nouvelles, avec accompagnement de harpe ou forté piano
=260  \\$aParis$bDes Lauriers$c1784
=300  \\$a27 pages$bTwo separate sheets with vla, hn and basso parts
=500  \\$aThe first appearance of the evergreen "Plaisir d'amour"
=505  \\$gD'instant qu'on nous mit en ménage -- L'Autre jour j'étois seule -- Dans la prairie et sous l'ormeau -- Malgré moi je frémis de votre loy -- Quel effroi pour ma tendresse -- Ah si parfois j'ay d'la tristesse -- Ce soir en votre honneur et gloire -- Plaisir d'amour (dans Célestine, nouvelle de Mr le Chr de Florian) -- En vain j'adresse au ciel (Romance de Fabian dans le Roman de Galatée; duet) -- O toy qui suis toujours mes pas ('Galatée et son chien')
=534  \\$a'Le Droit du Seigneur' is a comédie en cinq acts by Voltaire, premiered in Ferney in 1763, and set by Martini in 1783, see 15F20 for a full score
=590  \\$aL'auteur de la musique de cet ouvrage s'est vû obligé de faire lui-même des accompagnemens de harpe ou de forté piano à ses airs pour les réhabiliter tous ceux qui ont été faits jusqu'à présent n'étant nulemen conformes à la partition. Outre les accompagnements de harpe ou de Forte Piano il y a des parties de violons alto et basses pour les trois romances pour pouvoir être accompagnées avec l'orquestre.

=059  \\$aS pf
=100  \\$aKotschoubey,  Princess Elisabeth Vassilievna $d1821-1897$4cmp$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q102284079$98702
=245  \\$aOh ! dites-lui. Romance $bchantée par Tamberlick
=260  \\$aMainz$bSchott$c1861
=300  \\$a[1]-3 pages$bEngraved title page
=490  \\$a'Lyre Française'$vno. 783.1070
=500  \\$asong by a female composer, a member of the Ukrainian princely family Kotschoubey. Princess Elisabeth Vassilievna Kotschoubey (née Kotschoubey) (1821-1897) was a well known composer of both Russian and French popular songs in Russia and later in France. She was  married to her third cousin, Prince Leon Viktorovitch Kotschoubey (1810-1890) and they died childless. 
=500  \\$aEnrico Tamberlik (16 March 1820 – 13 March 1889) was an Italian tenor who sang to great acclaim at Europe and America's leading opera venues. He excelled in the heroic roles of the Italian and French repertories and was renowned for his powerful declamation and clarion high notes.
=500  \\$aText writer Larmande was a French state official (chef de bureau au Ministère des Finances), and amateur poet. Known for translating German songs, or rather for providing them with new, French poetry, e.g. in the series Échos d'Allemagne, together with Victor Wilder. His official signature (e.g. on his appointment as Chevalier de la légion d'honneur in 1881) always reads "Ad. Larmande", and his brother Alfred Larmande and sister-in-law Sophie Desargues were professional musicians.
=500  \\$aErnesto Cavallini (1807-74) clarinetist and composer, created in 1862 'Trois Variations sur la romance Oh!Dites-Lui' for Clarinet and orchestra:
https://imslp.org/wiki/3_Variations_sur_la_Romance_Russe_Chante_(Cavallini%2C_Ernesto)

=100  \\$aVoormolen, Alexander$d1895-1980$4cmp$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q2281256$96188
=245  \\$aCecilia (Oud Nederlandsch)
=246  \1$aCecilia. Middeleeuwsch Lied
=260  \\$aNetherlands$c1922
=300  \\$a5 pages
=500  \\$aPrinted and manuscript (Autograph?) version of the same song
=500  \\$aperformer's notes and markings in pensil on the manuscript version
=500  \\$acomposition place and date marked on manuscript version "'s-Gravenhage 1922"
=500  \\$aThis love song "Ik zag Cecilia komen" about the shepherds Cecilia and Floriaan, dates back to the 17th century. The oldest entry is in the Album of Geesken ter Borch (1652), with the opening line "Siet het pluijm gevogelt". The famous line with Cecilia is only found in verse 2 of the 2nd strophe. It also appears as "Lied van Cecilia" in the 'Dordrecht Helikon, ofte De Groote Dubbele Hollandsche Nachtegael' (1719). The song has lived on in the oral tradition, perhaps partly due to the fact that it has been included in numerous collections of folk songs. The melody is vaguely found in the Ballo di Mantova (Dance from Mantua) attributed to the guitar virtuoso Francisco Corbetta (1615-1681) and in "Fuggi fuggi da questo cielo" by Giuseppino Cenci (Giuseppino di Roma).
=561  \\$aManuscript version dedicated by the composer to Birgit Engell

=500  \\$aThe English organist, musicologist and writer, WaIter (Henry James) Emery, studied organ at the Royal Academy of Music in London. He has been engaged as a church organist & choir master. From 1937 to 1969 he was an associate at Novello & Co. where he edited works of early music (mainly for organ). He mainly published writings on the (organ) works of Johann Sebastian Bach.

=245  \\$aTwee Koraalvoorspelen in Barokstijl voor orgel met pedaal:$bHoe zal ik U ontvangen/Valet will ich dir geben - O God die droeg ons voorgeslacht/O God our help in ages past

=500  \\$aprinted facsimile copy of the manuscript autograph
=500  \\$aNancy van der Elst was a female composer who taught in Utrecht
=500  \\$atranslation of Paul Gerhardt's Advent song "Wie soll ich dich empfangen"
=500  \\$a"Valet will ich dir geben" is a Lutheran hymn written by Valerius Herberger in 1613. It is a Sterbelied (hymn for the dying). The text was published with two hymn tunes by Melchior Teschner, Zahn Nos. 5403 and 5404a, in 1615. The second of these melodies was used in compositions such as chorale preludes by Johann Sebastian Bach and Max Reger. Bach used single stanzas in vocal works, including his St John Passion.
=500  \\$a"Our God, Our Help in Ages Past" is a hymn by Isaac Watts in 1708 that paraphrases the 90th Psalm of the Book of Psalms. In 1738, John Wesley in his hymnal, Psalms and Hymns, changed the first line of the text from "Our God" to "O God". Both Watts' wording and Wesley's rewording remain in current use.
=500  \\$ain folder that contains another 2 paged organ-prelude to the chorale "Our God..." by Willem Hendrik Zwart, organist at the Bovenkerk of Kampen (in memory of his "memorable mother-in-law Mrs A.C.Hofland-de Smit, happy mother of many children")

=100  \\$aKeyserling, Herman Karl von$d1697-1765$4aut$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q959445$98802

=500  \\$aCount Hermann Karl von Keyserling from the Keyserlingk family of Baltic German nobility based in the Duchy of Courland and Semigallia, was a Russian diplomat under Catharina the Great and patron of Johann Sebastian Bach. At the time of the letters he was active as Russian envoy in Dresden.
=500  \\$aHe reports here to "Ewr. Königliche Hoheit" (Your Royal Highness), "Herzogin, Gnädigste(r) Fürstin und Frau" (who is possibly Elisabeth Sophie von Brandenburg, Duchess of Courland (Kurland). 1674-1748), about his activities (correspondence, financial matters, etc.), and affirms 'My eagerness to place myself at the feet of Your Royal Highness is certainly great..." (Meine Begierde, mich Ewr. Königliche Hoheit zu Füssen zu legen, ist gewiss gross...).
=500  \\$a Kurland/Courland is one of the historical and cultural regions in western Latvia.

=245  \\$aRembrandt van Rijn$b[Algemeen Handelsblad, 1852]
=260  \\$aAmsterdam$bDrukkerij van het Algemeen Handelsblad$c1852
=300  \\$a6 pages$billustrations
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$aNewspaper extract of the Algemeen Handelsblad of 28 mai 1852 (an influential Amsterdam-based liberal daily newspaper published between 1828 and 1970), on the occasion of King Willem III unveiling in 1852 a cast-iron Rembrandt monument designed by Louis Royer on the Amsterdam Botermarkt-square (named Rembrandtplein since 1876). 
=500  \\$a4 pages Biography, ending with poem by Thijm, plus 2 pages text that appeared on the title page of the Newspaper.
=500  \\$aThe biography ends with a long celebrating poem on Rembrandt by J.A. Alberdingk Thijm (1820-1889) titled "Een Harptoon in het Akkoord der Rembrandtshulde"
https://www.dbnl.org/tekst/albe003voor01_01/albe003voor01_01_0016.php

=LDR  05034aas a2200241   4500

=008  211027s1799\\\\\\\|||n|\||||\00|\0\ger\d
=041  \\$ager
=245  \\$aUnter Allerhöchster Autoriteit Ihro Kön. Maj. zu Dännemark, Norwegen u. Schleswig-Holsteinische Anzeigen 40stes Stück. Montag den 7ten October 1799
=260  \\$as.l.$bs.n.$c1799
=300  \\$a4 pages$bquadruple-folded pages$c42x36c cm
=336  \\$aprinted
=500  \\$aThe Schleswig-Holsteinische Anzeigen (SchlHA) is the justice journal of the German federal state of Schleswig-Holstein and at the same time one of the oldest periodicals of the state.
The Schleswig-Holsteinische Anzeigen date back to the time of the duchies of Schleswig and Holstein and have been published since 1750.[1] They are an announcement journal that was published under the same title by both the kings of Denmark and the diverse rulers in Schleswig-Holstein such as the House of Schleswig-Holstein-Gottorf. Today, the publisher is the state's Ministry of Justice, which has left the editorship to the Higher Regional Court of Schleswig. They are divided into a monthly Part A (with the editorial content of a legal journal and contributions on case law in the judicial district of the state's only Higher Regional Court) and a twice-monthly Part B (advertising section and judicial notices). It is therefore an official journal and not an advertising journal.
Part B of the Schleswig-Holstein Advertisements was published twice a month (on the 15th and 30th of a month) in printed form as a justice gazette until the end of 2014. The publication of a written edition of Part B has been dispensed with since 1 January 2015. Therefore, from this date onwards, all issues of Part B (which in future will only be published once on the 30th of a month) will only be made available digitally and free of charge.

=500  \\$aRoger de Rabutin, comte de Bussy, commonly known as Bussy-Rabutin, was a French memoirist, a lieutenant-general in the armies of King Louis XIV, a courtier at the French court, a philosopher and epistolary writer, a pamphleteer, a satirist and a libertine, and a member of the Académie française. He was the cousin and frequent correspondent of Madame de Sévigné.

=100  \\$aJourdez, A.$4asn$98864
=245  \\$aQuestions sur les mathématiques en général
=260  \\$as.l.$cc. 1730 [?]
=300  \\$a360 pages$bleather bound, red edges, marbled endpapers, gilded embossed spine
=500  \\$aUnfinished ms. containing 273 questions and answers.
=500  \\$aoriginates from a Benectine monastery school ?
=500  \\$aEx libris "Dom Antoine Jourdez", the last Benedictine monk of Toul, who wrote a handwritten document, entitled Description of the organ, 1811 and 1813. Attached to this 422-page manuscript is a 47-page Supplement, written in 1882, by Joseph Oury, organist of Toul Cathedral. The organ of the former Saint-Étienne Cathedral of Toul (Meurthe-et-Moselle) seemed to have passed through the Revolution without incident. When the church reopened, the last of the Benedictine monks of Saint-Mansuy, Dom Antoine Jourdez, had the organ restored and assumed the position of organist until September 30, 1828.

=043  \\$ae-ne---
=100  \\$aEkkart, Rudolf E. O.$4aut$910709
=245  10$aLief & leed:$brealisme en fantasie in Nederlandse familiegroepen uit de zeventiende en achttiende eeuw
=246  3\$aLief en leed
=264  \1$aZwolle:$bWaanders$aEnschede$bRijksmuseum Twenthe$c2018
=300  \\$a208 pages :$billustrations (chiefly color), portraits ;$c27 cm
=336  \\$atext$btxt$2rdacontent
=336  \\$astill image$bsti$2rdacontent
=337  \\$aunmediated$bn$2rdamedia
=338  \\$avolume$bnc$2rdacarrier
=504  \\$aIncludes bibliographical references (pages 198-202) and index.
=505  0\$aInleiding -- Families in beeld: de ontwikkeling van de familiegroep vanaf de zestiende eeuw -- Realisme en fantasie: Nederlandse familiegroepen en andere portretten -- De herkenbare dood: overleden gezinsleden in het familieportret -- De vermomde dood: schijnbaar levende gezinsleden in het familieportret -- Gezinsuitbreiding: bijgeschilderde familieleden -- Slotwoord.
=520  8\$a"Familieportretten uit de Gouden Eeuw, maar ook later, verbeelden de schone schijn. Op het eerste gezicht lijken zij realistisch, maar dat blijkt lang niet altijd het geval. Op verzoek van hun opdrachtgevers maakten portretschilders uit de 17de en 18de eeuw zich geregeld schuldig aan 'beeldmanipulatie'. Overleden personen zijn als levend afgebeeld en met een huwelijk of geboorte werden nieuwe familieleden bijgeschilderd. Na een flinke ruzie werden figuren net zo makkelijk ook weer gewist uit de voorstelling. Met een kritische blik en jaren van onderzoek laten de auteurs zien dat zelfs in de portretkunst, het ogenschijnlijk meest waarheidsgetrouwe genre in de beeldende kunst, de waarheid niet altijd even nauw wordt genomen. De mooiste verhalen komen aan het licht. Verhalen over perfecte huwelijken en verboden liefdes. Over de plotselinge dood en de vreugde van nieuw leven. Over het lief en leed van het familiebestaan"--$cPublisher's website.
=546  \\$aIn Dutch, with a summary in English.

=100  \\$aJas, Eric$4aut$911853
=245  13$aDe Leidse koorboeken:$been ongehoorde schat
=260  \\$aZoetermeer$bBoekencentrum$c2011
=300  \\$a88 p. :$bill., music ;$c25 cm.
=520  8\$aVan de honderden koorboeken die Nederland in de zestiende eeuw rijk was, is slechts een dertiental bewaard gebleven. Zes van deze enorme, prachtige en handgeschreven boeken - een unieke, kostbare muziekschat - werden speciaal gemaakt voor het koor van de Leidse Pieterskerk, dat daar dagelijks de zeven getijden uit zong. Tot aan de Reformatie. Toen verdwenen ze voor eeuwen in een kist. Dit rijk geïllustreerde boekje vertelt het verhaal van de Leidse Koorboeken. Het leest als een spannende novelle, waarin naast de boeken ook deftige families, kleurrijke componisten, grafgangen, de handel in jongenssopranen, luie zangers en beeldenstormers een belangrijke rol spelen.

=500  \\$aWerner Wolffheim was a German lawyer and musicologist with a majorly important music collection. The auction sale of his library in 1928 and 1929 was an important event in the world of (early) music, musicology, and book collectors. A large part of the collection was bought by Paul Hirsch.

=500  \\$aAutograph dedication on tp
=500  \\$aAmédée Reuchsel was a French composer and organist. He studied music at the Conservatories of Brussels and Paris; in the latter he had as teacher in composition the master Gabriel Fauré. He obtained the position of organist of the church of Saint Dionysus in Paris and in 1908 he was awarded the Chartier prize for chamber music. His father Léon (1840-1915) was also a musician, as were his brother Maurice (1880-1968) and his son Eugène (1900-1988).

=500  \\$aCornelis van Alkemade was a Dutch historian and a passionate collector of antiquities, both coins and old manuscripts. Through his many publications, Van Alkemade acquired great authority in his time as a connoisseur of antiquities.
=500  \\$aPieter van der Schelling was a Dutch historian, collector and researcher of antiquities, who, after his marriage in 1717 to Alida van Alkemade began working with his father-in-law Cornelis van Alkemade, also a collector of antiquities. After Cornelis van Alkemade's death in 1737, Pieter van der Schelling continued his work.

=100  \\$aHaydn, Joseph$d1732-1809$4cmp$1http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q7349$94783
=245  \\$aA Select Collection of Original Scottish Airs for the Voice$nVol. 1
=250  \\$a2st ed. 
=260  \\$aLondon$aEdinburg$bPreston$bThomson$c[1803]
=300  \\$a[i]-4-[ii]-100-[i]- pages$balternating pages of text and music, Vols. 1, 3 and 4 in a blue custom made case, engraved ill. as frontispiece.
=500  \\$a"A Select Collection of Original Scottish Airs for the Voice" is a multi-volume collection of Scottish song edited and published by the entrepreneurial musician, publisher and Clerk to the Board of Trustees for Encouragement of Art and Manufacture in Scotland, George Thomson. For the first volume, which appeared in 1793, Thomson commissioned the composer Ignaz Pleyel to provide musical settings.

From the Preface of Vol. 3: "For the composition of these [the symphonies and accompaniments], he entered into terms with Mr Pleyel, who fulfilled part of his engagement very satisfactorily; but having then deserted it, the Editor, after a fruitless correspondence with him, which retarded the progress of the Work for years, at length found it necessary to turn his eyes elsewhere. He was so fortunate, however, [...] as to engage Mr Kozeluch and Dr Haydn, to proceed with the Work, which they have finished in such a manner, as to leave him without any other regret, but that of having so long delayed his application to them." 

This is the second edition of the first volume, published in 1803, in which Thomson has replaced 21 of the previously published version with settings by Haydn.  
=500  \\$aContains a full page engraved illustration "The Birks of Invermay Soldier's Return".
=500  \\$aWith Thomson's signature on title page.
=501  \\$aIn a case with Vols. 3 and 4 of the same collection. See also G2-001.
=590  \\$aWith Introductory & Concluding Symphonies & Accompaniments for the Piano Forte, Violin & Violoncello by Pleyel, Kozeluch & Haydn. With Select & Characteristic Verses both Scottish and English adapted to the Airs, including upwards of One Hundred New Songs by Burns.

=500  \\$a"A Select Collection of Original Scottish Airs for the Voice" is a multi-volume collection of Scottish song edited and published by the entrepreneurial musician, publisher and Clerk to the Board of Trustees for Encouragement of Art and Manufacture in Scotland, George Thomson. For the first volume, which appeared in 1793, Thomson commissioned the composer Ignaz Pleyel to provide musical settings.

From the Preface of the first edition of Vol. 3: "For the composition of these [the symphonies and accompaniments], he entered into terms with Mr Pleyel, who fulfilled part of his engagement very satisfactorily; but having then deserted it, the Editor, after a fruitless correspondence with him, which retarded the progress of the Work for years, at length found it necessary to turn his eyes elsewhere. He was so fortunate, however, [...] as to engage Mr Kozeluch and Dr Haydn, to proceed with the Work, which they have finished in such a manner, as to leave him without any other regret, but that of having so long delayed his application to them."
